included.description: The Center for the Education of Women (CEW) is redesigning their website in order to attract young women and nontraditional students. More specifically, the organization wanted to attract individuals who may be interested in scholarships and the Women of Color Task Force Conference. As part of the needs assessment and usability evaluation process, our group created an interaction map, deployed a survey, performed interviews, a comparative analysis, usability tests, and a heuristic evaluation. Key findings were presented to be implemented in their next iteration of the website.
included.title: The Center for the Education of Women

included.description: Through seasonal changes, leaves fall from trees in preparation for the winter. The result is streets filled with fallen leaves that impeded traffic and daily travel. The Department of Public Works (DPW) in Ferndale collects these leaves as a part of a city millage. However, the sheer abundance of leaves makes it difficult for residents and DPW to manage. Our group conducted interviews and deployed surveys for the city residents to better understand the problem. We created a two-pronged approach in informing residents of Ferndale with a low-tech flyer and a high-tech widget for the city's website.
included.title: Leaf Life: My City Served

included.description:
The University of Michigan Conferences and Events Services plans events, conferences, and catering for student organizations, faculty, and external clients and businesses. Recently, three separate organizations combined into one: the Union Services, Conferences and Events Services, and the Catering Services. However, as a result of the merge, the three groups have segmented and disjointed channels of communication. This has lead to unwanted confusion and inefficiency.

To better understand the different groups, contextual inquiry interviews were done. Participants in the interviews were members from all three organizations. Additionally, employees at all levels were interviewed. Doing so gave us all the different possible perspectives there are in the organization.

Once contextual inquiries and reports were written, our group conducted an affinity diagram exercise to find converging points of either contention or agreement between the different employees.
included.title: The University of Michigan Conferences and Events Services
